{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696398/1930111801/0823.xml":{"full_text":"2\nCONGRESS BESIEGED WITH REQUESTS FOR CASH BONUS FOR VETS\nW TO 0. S.\nHID IT\n31ILLM\nMovement Sponsored as Way\nTo: Bring About Return of\nProsperity; Putman Active\nDemands for payment of\nColdlers' adjusted service compen\nsation certificates in cash, total\nling upwards of $3,000,000,000,\nare rolling in upon members of\nCongress.\nReturning members report that\ndefinite movements are under\nway in many sections to create\nSentiment for the proposal.\nAlthough the Treasury has\nOpposed the plan, the pressure\nbehind the movement may make\nIt a live issue immediately after\nshe session opens in December.\n30 Bills Submitted\nMore than 30 members have\nintroduced bills to this effect in\nthe house, and more bills are\nexpected early next month. The\nfirst move of backers of the move\nment will be a demand for a\nhearing before the House Ways\n\u2022nd Means Committee.\nRepresentative Wright Patman\n[(D.) of Texas, said today the\nproposal has gathered strength\nas a measure of speeding business\nby increasing the buying power\nOs veterans. He has received re-,\nports that Treasury experts are\nstudying the situation. He said:\n\u201cUp to October 1, a total of\n1,433,111 veterans had bor\nrowed money from the Veter\nans Bureau on their adjusted\nservice certificates, out of 3,-\n6tt,000 outstanding. Experts of\nthe Bureau estimate that bor\nrowings from banks bring the\ntotal of veterans borrowing\nmoney up to 75 per cent of\ncertificates of any considerable\nvalue.\nSinking Fund Noted\n\u201cThe Government' now has\n\u2022bout $700,000,000 in a sinking\nfund to meet the certificates\nupon maturity. A note issue of\ntwo billion dollars probably\nwould be sufficient io give the\n..veterans their choice of 80 per\nXjeeut face value or keeping the\n'.certificates until maturity. The\ncertificates could be retired by\nthe Treasury in five years.\n\u201cThe average value of the\ncertificate is $1,013, and it is\nestimated that payment of the\nentire amount' would immedi\nately raise the money in circu\nrlation from $35 to 49 per capi\nj to, and thus provide a suffi\nt dent circulating medium to as\nsure good times.\u201d\nThe American Lesion has not\n\u00a3aken a position on the proposal,\nshut several other veterans'organi\nsations have endorsed it,\nPa Pont Will Filed;\nProvisions Secret\nWILMINGTON, Del., Nov. 18\nJCINH.).\u2014The will of Gen. Cole\nman du Pont was filed here\ntoday. His widow, Mrs. Alice\n\u2022du Pont, and his son, Frank T.\njHu Pont, were named executors.\nIt is understood the members\n\u2022pf the family are the chief bene\nficiaries and that there were no\nJeharitable bequests as trust\nfunds already had been provided.\nNeither the provisions of the\ndocument nor an estimate of\n.the amount of the fortune were\n\u2022vailable.\nDEATH HELD MISHAP\nALEXANDRIA, Nov. 17.\u2014Fair-\nTfax County Coroner C. A. Ransom\na certificate of accidental\nj death in the case of Osha Almond\n\u201cnine, of Hunters Station, who was\n-khot by Jock Nightingale. 11,\n'While playing with a small rifle\n3>ear their homes Saturday.\ni-\nFor the First Ten\nMonths of 1930\nJ The Washington Times\nGAINED\n444,146 Lines\nOs Local Display\nAdvertising.\nj: The Washington Herald\nGAINED\ni 157,169 Lines\n(Daily Only)\nI F\n8 The Other Evening Paper:\nlost\ni 448,889 Lines\n(Daily Only)\n\n(The Other Morning Paper\ni ::WST\n252,014 Lines\nv 5 -(Daily Only)\nAH n<ni*\u00bb 1 from\nMEDIA .RECORDS. INC.\nlaoM' Ciw**\u00ab Oslr\nPlan Religious Debate Here Tonight\nI\nBl\n\u2014Tlmsa Start Photo\nRABBI SIMON DARROW O\u2019BRIEN REV. PIERCE\nHERE ARE THE FOUR MEN who tonight will debate religion. They are shown\nat breakfast at the Willard. Rabbi Simon, of the Washington Hebrew Congregation;\nClarence Darrow, Chicago attorney; Quin O\u2019Brien, Chicago attorney and Catholic lay\nman, and the Rev. Dr. Jason Noble Pierce, of First Congregational Church, are pictured*\nMESSAGE URGES\nLEGGE TO QUIT\nThe immediate resignation of\nAlexander Legge, chairman of\nthe Federal Farm Board, would\nbe \u201ca wonderful Christmas pres\nent to the taxpayers\u201d in the opin\nion of Max Lavand and Louis Le\nvand, Wichita, Kan., publishers,\ncontained in a telegram received\ntoday by Chairman Legge.\nIt \u00bbwas recently reported that\nMr. Legge may resign from office\non January 1, and official circles\nhave been stirred by the report.\n\u201cAlexander Legge: You an\u00bb\nnounce you may resign on Janu\nary 1. Tbe people of Kansas\nurge you to resign immediately.\nYour latest affront pto Kansas\nin refusing the request of Sena\ntor Capper for an audience\nwith the co-operatives on the\nground you were too busy is\nunheard of in the annals of\ndemocratic government, arous\ning the people to the point of\ndemanding you to step out nt\nonce to permit the appointment\nof a man who can do. the job\nat which you have so signally\nfailed.\n\u201cYour failure to consider the\nsuggestion of Governor Reed\nthat the board buy 25,060,000\nbushels of wheat to stabilise\nthe market was another direct\ninsult to the Kansas farmers\nwhom Mr. Reed represented.\nSix weeks remain before. Janu\nary 1. A good man in your,\nplace could do wonders in that\ntime. Your resignation will be\n2 aided as a wonderful Christ\ns gift to the taxpayers.\u201d\nEurope's Next Royal Bridal Couple\nJr-\n|F/ 4BRIM& W-' IMtW\n.JM .3\n4U li?\nBk i\u00dfk,\nHkjK;\nif il&llik\nH E9F W\nW Oik- Jg ffifer-\nV d| dfl h\nF sr* bm A\n\\V k w O'\nIMMi BB IlmjME\nwt M WKS WWg Wg W -\u25a0'\u2022fwWw\noIsSWIIHi KKK.\nar\n\u2014lnternattcnal New\u00bbr eel\ni PRINCE CHRISTOPHER AND PRINCESS SOPHIE\nHERE IS THE FIRST PICTURE rot Europe\u2019s next royal bridal couple. Prince\nChristopher of Hesse and. Princess Sophie of Greece are shown together with a pet on\nthe occasion of their first joint appearance before the camera. The couple will be\nmarried at Frankfort, December 15.\nTHE WASHINCTOH TIMU\nPEOPLE\u2014You Read About\nWoman Hurt by Auto\nSues Wife of Broker\nNEW YORK, Nov. 18.\u2014The\nViennese actress who married\nPercy K. Hudson, |New York\nbroker, and\nthen divorced\nhim, is the de\nfendant in a\nSIOO,OOO dam\nage suit.\nMiss Marion\nLyon, former\nshow girl and\nmodel, has\nbrought suit\nagainst Mrs.\nHudson for that\namount, charg\ning that she\nwas seriously\ninjured by a\nmachine driven \u00bb*w\nby Mrs. Hudson near Lage George\nlast year.\nHarriet Huntington\nMarries an Iceman\nPASADENA, Calif., Nov. 18.\nMiss Harriet Green Huritington,\ngranddaughter and heiress to the\nr\ndHp SB\n9k\nMr*. Borrr\n\u25a0\u25a0p mH\nmillions of the\nlate Henry E.\nH u n t i n gton,\nhas married an\niceman.\nShe became\nthe bride yes\nterday of Albert\nDoerr, J,r.,\nathlete who\nworked his way\nthrough college\nby driving an\nicewagon. H e\nonce took Miss\nHuntington to\na dance in this\nvehicle.\nFamily \"Takes to Air\u201d\nWith African Lion Cub\nThe Hutchinson family has be\ncome \u201cair minded.\u201d\nFirst it was George R. Hutchin\nson, who took up flying and liked\nit. Then Mrs.\nBlanche Hutch\ninson took to\nthe air. With\nboth mother\nand father fly\ning, there was\nnothing to do\nbut take the\nchildren up.\nSo now Blanche\nCatherine, 7,\nand Janet Lee,\n4, are both en\nthusiasts.\nSeveral\nmonths ago a\nfriend sent\nF\nyx-\n-t V f\nMrs. Hutchinson\nHutchinson a lion cub from Africa,\nand now even the cub has 30 hours\nof flying time.\n8 to Testify Capone\nHolds Police Power\nCHICAGO, Nov. 18 (I JUS.).\nAn answer to the question of\nwhether' Alphonse Capone in\nfluences police department af\nfairs was awaited today with\nthe appearance of eight police\nofficers, including a captain and\na lieutenant, before the Novem\nber Grand Jury.\nIt is alleged they were trans\nferred into outlying districts\nwhen they refused the bribes\nof a Capone lieutenant after\nwaging war on several of the\ngang leader's gambling houses.\nEach was offered SIOO a week\nfor his cooperation, it was said.\ntl, rt\nNational\nHOOVER'S BOARD\nDEAOLOGKED\nON RUH\nLaw Enforcement Group Split\nSo Widely on Views, General\nReport -le Held Unlikely\nBy GEORGE R. HOLMES\nPresident Hoover\u2019s Law En\nvided in its views on prohibition\nforcement Commission is so dl\nthat H is wholly unlikely it can\nproduce any report which win\nnot be the subject of controversy\namong its own members, much\nless the public.\nSince the commission went into\nretirement some days ago to\nwrestle with its problem, all sorts\nof rumors have flitted about. It\nhas been variously reported that\nthe commission would ultimately\nrecommend retention of the\nEighteenth Amendment; that it\n.would indorse modification of the\nVolstead act up to 4 per cent\nbeer; that it would favor a sort\nof modified Canadian system of\ncontrol, and that it would pro\npose a national constitutional\nconvention to solve the liquor\nproblem.\nAB of 'Em Denied\nAll of these rumors haye been\ndenied at one stage or another,\nand. seemingly, with some justice.\nThe fact is, according to the\nmost authoritative sources, that\nthe commissioners are so badly\nsplit that they not only cannot\nagree on what changes, if any,\nare to be recommended in exist\ning law, but they cannot agree as\nto the fundamental right of the\ncommission to propose any change\nin any law.\nSeveral members take the view\nthat it is not within the province\nof the commission to recommend\nchanges in the laws; that it is\nthe sole duty of the commission\nto Suggest ways and means of se\ncuring better enforcement of tbe\nlaws now existent.\nThey point to the name of the\nbody itself, as given by President\nHoover, \u201cThe National Commis\nsion on Law Observance and En\nforcement.\u201d There is nothing in\nthat title, they say, that suggests\nany law revision.\nMinority to Report\nA majority of the Commission,\nhowever, does not agree with this\nview. But even in the majority\nthat does not agree there is no\nunanimity of opinion as to just\nhow far the Commission may go\nin proposing modification.\nAs to what will be the ultimate\noutcome of the deliberations and\ndivided counsels only the future\ncan tell. The members them\nselves do not like to hazard\nguesses, for the differences are\nso great and so apparently deep\nrooted that it is considered im\nprobable a report can be written\nthat will command the support\nof more than seven of the eleven\nmembers. That there will be a\nmajority report and one. or more,\nminority reports seems assured.\nENGEL INQUEST\nDUE TODAY\nFuneral arrangements for Bry\nant Engel. 9-year-old son of Joe\nEngel, president of the Chatta\nnooga Baseball Club and scout of\nthe Washington Baseball Club,\nwill not be completed until the ar\nrival of his father. The boy was\nkilled last night by an automobile\ndriven by Eldridge Keedy, of 1701\nPark Rd. N. W.. in front of the\nEngel home at 1629 Columbia Rd.\nK. W.\nEngel is now racing across the\ncountry aboard a train from Bel\nClair, Tex., where he had been on\na hunting trip. Clark Griffith,\npresident of the Washington Base\nball Club, notified him of the\ndeath.\nJust Got Divorce\nThe accident occurred just a\nfew hours after Mrs. Engel had\nobtained a divorce, alimony and\nthe custody of Brya'ht in the Dis\ntrict Supreme Court. She charged\nEngel with desertion and with\ncalling her insulting names.\nBryant was returning to his\nhome after playing when he was\nstruck by the Keedy automobile.\nHe was thrown against a parked\nautomobile and his head crushed.\nKeedy rushed the boy to Emer\ngency Hospital, where he was pro\nnounced dead.\nMrs. Engel was notified shortly\nafter the accident, but reached\nthe hospital too late to see her\nboy alive.\nCar Headed East\nKeedy said he was going east\non Columbia Road when the boy\nran between his car and another\ntravelling in the opposite direc\ntion. He was taken to the Tenth\nprecinct, but was released in the\ncare of his attorney until the\ninquest which iftn be held at\n11 a.,m. tomorrow.\nIn addition to the divorce and\ncustody of the boy, Mrs. Engel\nwas awarded $275 a month\nalimony by Justice WilUam Hitz.\nShe married the former big\nleague pitcher in Union City,\nTenn., tn 1916. She said in her\npetition that Engel\u2019s income is\nSIO,OOO a year.\nTUESDAY-NOVEMBER IS-IS3O\nI*2 Workers lulled Us Scaffold.\nI _ U< J\nWORKERS AROUND BODIES AFTER FALL. _.\nI w\n1 1111 tTH 'W'\nHIF f m\nfl* I /-I I\nIS 4 it li HI\nrw a ifs S I\n11^<> 4 Bib Bl fl\n\nEr? Rr'WlHMMtt l' Ml J f S BBttIfIBBBIBBBBr\nli\nr l 4\nKs mt 51 1 t\ni ti\nBflfl\u00df\u00dffl\u00dfflfl\u00df\u00df\u00df\u00dfflfl\u00df\u00df\u00dfl^H^^^^B\u00dfi\u00dfliil\u00df\u00dfflKi^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^B^B,\ni\nIhRMSK r <1\nttdMrJnFA\n\nO\u2019 9K\nBm99X\u00ab*\nWHERE SWINGNG SCAFFOLD FELL\n8m STEALS\nSON BY PLANE\nCHICAGO, Nov. 11 (LNJ3J.\nMrs. Grace Rycroft Colonell, in\nternationally known beauty and\nwife of Frank Colonell, New York\nbroker, was speeding East today\nafter evading deputy sheriffs\narmed with warrants for her ar\nrest.\nMrs. Colonell is charged with\nhaving \u201ckidnaped\u201d her 7-year-oH\nson, by a fo/mer marriage, from\na desert military school. The\nwarrants were sworn out by her\ndivorced husband, Herbert D. Ry\ncroft. Each was awarded cus\ntody of the Child for one year.\nOne month ago Mrs. Colonell\nwon complete custody of the boy\nand found him in a school at\nTaft, Calif. She brought him\nhere in an airplane.\nHer former husband imme\ndiately secured warrants charg\ning her with kidnaping and post\ned\u00bb rewards fs>r her apprehension.\nCHURCH HOLDS BAZAAR\nALEXANDRIA. Va., Nov. 18.\nA basaar for the benefit of St.\nMary\u2019s Catholic Church will be\nheld in the armory beginning to\nmorrow evening and closing Sat\nurday night*\nNEW TIPS GIVEN\nINBAKEfIGfiSE\nTwo new leads which may lead\nto a solution of the slaying of\nMary Baker are being investi\ngated by Washington police to\nday. x\nThe inquiries were revealed\nwhen Detective Sergeant John\nFlaherty, head at the homicide\nsquad, left the city on a secret\nmission.\nWhile his destination was\ncarefully shielded, it is under\nstood that ownership of a scarf\nfound with the murdered girl\u2019s\nclothing in a culvert a few days\nafter her bullet riddled body /as\nfound, April 11, has definitely\nbeen established.\nSergeant Flaherty will visit\ntwo cities as a result of informa\ntion which reached Inspector\nWilliam Shelby last Sunday.\nThe inspector declined to go\ninto details as to the nature of\nthe information.\nBANK STATEMENT\nNew York, Clearing House ex\nchange, $1,142,000,000.\nNew York Clearing House bal\nance, $148,000,000.\nCustom receipts. $18,834,820.21.\nTreasury balance, $98,311,502.62.\n\u2014Time* Staff 'RB\u00abP>\u00ab\nWORKERS AROUND BODIES\nHERBERT JETT, a stone pol\nisher. of 1214 C St. S. W, and\nJohn Jones, a sub-contractor,\nwere killed this morning when\na swinging scaffold, being\nlowered between the sixth and\nseventh floors of the new\nPotomac Electric Power Com\npany building, Tenth and E\nStreets Northwest, fell. It\nwas a scaffold similar to the\none at the right near the top of\nthe building in the lower pic\nture.\nCUHTISEYIGTIIIN\nSAVED BY SABO\n\nCHICAGO. Nov. 18 (IHJ3.).\nVice President Charles Curtis\ncould not bear to think of his son.\nAttorney Harry Curtis, being\nevicted from his home for non\npayment of rent, so he diig up\nS4OO in cash and telegraphed it\nhere.\nA bailiff, four assistants Mid a\nrepresentative of a Chicago bank\ndescended upon the younger Mr.\nCurtis\u2019 apartment yesterday -to\nevict him and place his furniture\nout on the street unless SBB7 in\nback rent was paid.\nOnly the attorney\u2019s young wife\nwas at home. Her protests failed\nto move the bailiff from his origi\nnal purpose unless the money was\nforthcoming.\nMrs. Curtis called the Vice Presi\ndent at Washington by telephone\nand permitted the bank represen\ntative to talk with her father-in\nlaw.\nAfter a hit of bargaining the\nbanker agreed that the bailiff and\nhis squad would be sent away, tem\nporarily, if S4OO were paid by wire.\nA messenger soon arrived with the\nrelief fund.\nThe Vice President is quoted as\nsaying:\n\"My son is on Ms way to Chi\ncago now, and will pay yon the\nrest.\"\nI\"\" 1 11\nSentenced\nt\nBL\nv JM\nIf gl. i rl\nBl K w\n\u25a0gp- HF\n\n~W\ni \u2014\u2019lnternatioaa! Newsreel\nKEMBLE K. KENNEDY\nKENNEDY, a senior law stu\ndent at Louisiana State Uni\nversity, expected a diploma: he\ngot a year in the State prison\ninstead. Governor Long, how\never, may pardon the student,\nwhose writings in an outlawed\nstudent publication were* held\nto constitute criminal libel","height":"30391","width":"24298"}}
